---
// src/pages/employees/index.astro
import BaseLayout from '../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
---

<BaseLayout
  door="employees"
  title="Get Paid"
  description="You already know you're worth more. Here's what collective bargaining looks like when the only agenda is compensation."
>

  <!-- ── Door Hero — Activation Register ───────────────── -->
  <div class="page-body">
    <section class="door-hero door-hero--employees" aria-label="Employees door">
      <p class="door-hero-eyebrow">Employees</p>
      <h1 class="door-hero-headline">
        You already know you're<br/><em>worth more.</em>
      </h1>
      <div class="door-hero-rule"></div>
      <p class="door-hero-sub">
        The skinny union is how you get it: collective bargaining focused entirely on pay.
        No &ldquo;full fat&rdquo; grievance apparatus, no job-security politics, no leverage
        spent on anything but your compensation.
      </p>
    </section>
  </div>

  <!-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════
       PLAIN-LANGUAGE CASE
  ════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->

  <!-- ── Piece 1: Bargaining Alone ─────────────────────── -->
  <div class="page-body">
    <section class="spec-section" aria-label="You make less money bargaining alone">
      <div class="col-structural">
        <span class="section-number">Part I</span>
        <span class="section-label section-label--crimson">The Information Asymmetry</span>
      </div>
      <div class="col-main">
        <h2 class="border-crimson">You make less money bargaining alone.</h2>

        <p>
          On one side of the table sits an institution with years of compensation data and a clear
          sense of what it can pay. On the other sits one person doing math against Glassdoor at
          midnight. The employee knows what she was offered. She knows it felt low. She negotiated,
          got two thousand dollars more, and told herself she had done well.
        </p>

        <p>
          She had not done well. She had done what every worker does who bargains alone against an
          institution: she had accepted the natural result of an information asymmetry she could
          not overcome individually. Her employer was not cheating. Her employer was doing what
          employers do — setting compensation at the lowest point the market will bear, one hire
          at a time. Her only real leverage would have been the collective kind: the ability to
          say, with all her colleagues standing behind her, that the organization's salary structure
          was a subject for negotiation, not announcement.
        </p>

        <p>
          She did not have that leverage. She had never been offered it.
        </p>

        <p>
          Because even with all the facts, even without being afraid of getting canned, it can
          still be scary to ask for more. Lots of people are great at their jobs, confident in
          their performance, and still uncomfortable in those one-on-one negotiations. Will the
          boss — who you actually like — be offended? What if they say no?
        </p>

        <p>
          Collective bargaining changes this. It puts you at a table where the agenda is less
          personal, less political, and entirely focused on the economics.
        </p>
      </div>
    </section>
  </div>

  <!-- ── Piece 2: The Switching Cost Problem ───────────── -->
  <div class="page-body">
    <section class="spec-section" aria-label="The switching cost problem">
      <div class="col-structural">
        <span class="section-number">Part II</span>
        <span class="section-label section-label--crimson">The Switching Cost Problem</span>
      </div>
      <div class="col-main">
        <h2 class="border-crimson">You shouldn't have to switch jobs to get paid the market rate.</h2>

        <p>
          Let's say you're a software engineer at a mid-size tech company, or a journalist at a
          media organization. Thanks to state laws requiring salary disclosures in job postings,
          you often see listings for similar roles that pay $20,000 more than you make. Three
          things are probably true.
        </p>

        <ul>
          <li>You could switch jobs and capture that extra $20,000. But that would be a lot of
          hassle — interviews, culture change, modified commutes, new bosses, new systems. As much
          as you want to be paid the market rate, you probably wouldn't leave a job you like and
          are good at without a more significant bump or a promotion.</li>

          <li>If you did leave, your employer would probably have to pay that extra $20,000 to
          replace you, plus recruitment costs. That's what the market bears now.</li>

          <li>Your employer is counting on you and most of your colleagues not to jump for lateral
          positions that pay a little more. They are counting on you just taking the 3% raise.</li>
        </ul>

        <p>
          Your employer, no matter how decent they are in every other way, is hell-bent on forcing
          you to switch jobs in order to keep up with the market for your services. What can be done
          about this?
        </p>

        <p>
          On the one hand, everyone knows the answer is collective bargaining. Unions.
        </p>

        <p>
          On the other hand, everyone also knows that unions are associated with devoting vast
          quantities of their members' limited bargaining power on things other than wages.
        </p>

        <p>
          What's needed is an organization that will allow employees to stay focused on what matters
          most: wages and benefits — so they can capture their full value without switching jobs.
          That is what the Skinny Union model provides.
        </p>
      </div>
    </section>
  </div>

  <!-- ── Licensed Break ────────────────────────────────── -->
  <div class="page-body">
    <div class="licensed-break licensed-break--crimson">
      <p>
        The employer is negotiating with a group whose coordinated exit, were it exercised,
        would be costly in a way that any individual's departure is not.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- ── Piece 3: What the Skinny Union Is ─────────────── -->
  <div class="page-body">
    <section class="spec-section" aria-label="What the skinny union is and is not">
      <div class="col-structural">
        <span class="section-number">Part III</span>
        <span class="section-label section-label--crimson">The Model</span>
      </div>
      <div class="col-main">
        <h2 class="border-crimson">What if you just got paid more?</h2>

        <p>
          Traditional unions negotiate complex agreements that include reams of provisions
          connected to non-wage items — discipline, grievance procedures, arbitration, seniority,
          shift assignments. These things are funded by significant dues paying for vast
          organizational capacity to manage those hearings and complex bargaining dynamics.
          And these things still matter for many kinds of careers.
        </p>

        <p>
          But not everyone who needs a union needs grievance procedures.
        </p>

        <p>
          The reality for many professional workers is that they operate in a liquid job market
          in jurisdictions with comprehensive protections against discrimination and bias that
          go far beyond what federal law provides. In short: these workers do not want a union
          to come in and spend leverage on all those non-wage items, on all that protection for
          poor performers, on all the internal politics that goes along with it. What they have
          not been offered is a path to use their collective bargaining power on what matters
          most to them: higher salaries and better benefits.
        </p>

        <p>
          The Skinny Union model does not touch hiring, performance management, or at-will
          employment. It does not create a grievance apparatus or a protection-of-poor-performers
          function. It does not constrain restructuring, slow down personnel decisions, or add
          organizational layers to the management relationship. Everything the professional
          worker's labor market depends on — meritocratic evaluation, accountability cultures,
          the employer's ability to act quickly when circumstances change — operates exactly as
          it would without a union in place.
        </p>

        <p>
          It is a precisely calibrated tool. Not the instrument a different generation of workers
          built for a different problem, but one designed for the problem you actually have.
        </p>
      </div>
    </section>
  </div>

  <!-- ── Piece 4: They Don't Think You Will ────────────── -->
  <div class="page-body">
    <section class="spec-section" aria-label="The cynics and the challenge">
      <div class="col-structural">
        <span class="section-number">Part IV</span>
        <span class="section-label section-label--crimson">The Challenge</span>
      </div>
      <div class="col-main">
        <h2 class="border-crimson">They don't think you will do it.</h2>

        <p>
          "It's a great idea, but they'll never do it." That's what top management counsel say
          about the Skinny Union. That's what the executive suite says. They have spent years
          dealing with traditional unions and they have one core belief: management looks at
          employment as an exercise in economics, and unions look at it as an exercise in politics.
        </p>

        <p>
          It is a cynical view. They think the workers who most want the union are the weakest
          performers, that their interests will dominate the politics of the organization, and
          that the union will trade money for job protection. Every. Single. Time.
        </p>

        <p>
          That objection deserves to be answered on the merits, not dismissed. We answer it in
          <a href="/press">The Argument</a>.
        </p>

        <p>
          But if you and your colleagues are genuinely motivated to challenge this cynicism — to
          organize for better pay and accept the existing employee handbook terms for everything
          else — you can do it, it will work, and you will get more money.
        </p>

        <p>
          Traditional unions are not going to provide this service. They have a different model
          and a different agenda. They want the grievance procedures, the arbitrations, the
          minimum staffing rules.
        </p>

        <p>
          The Skinny Union is here to ask: Are the cynics right?
        </p>
      </div>
    </section>
  </div>

  <!-- ── Closing Cross-Links ───────────────────────────── -->
  <div class="page-body">
    <section class="spec-section" aria-label="Where to go next">
      <div class="col-structural">
        <span class="section-number">Next</span>
        <span class="section-label section-label--crimson">Go Deeper</span>
      </div>
      <div class="col-main">
        <h2 class="border-crimson">Not convinced yet?</h2>
        <p>
          The full case — why traditional labor stalled, and what the skeptics get wrong — is
          in <a href="/press">The Argument</a>. The legal architecture, the labor market
          analysis, and the economics are in the white paper on <a href="/research">Research</a>.
        </p>
      </div>
    </section>
  </div>

</BaseLayout>
